@BasicMountain But in the grand scheme of things, I think the whole "argument" is really proxy for folks not liking Hoogland. I think where I end up falling is "I don't get why this is Discourse at all, and a QRT is the fastest way to get someone else to explain why it might be one."

@BasicMountain In a more targeted sense, this in the context of Ondrej's evidence being that people played Auras is awkward to me. There have been a TON of PTs where a ton of good players registered dogshit decks.

@BasicMountain But also, I am not putting as much of a value judgement on "gatekeeping" or "elitism" that Hoogland does. Both are deeply ingrained responses to any event/competition that purports to be exclusive, right? Having to Q for a PT at all is gatekeeping. That doesn't make it BAD.

@BasicMountain In general, these arguments tend to be circular. Because of the perceived (and earned) "elite" status of a PT regular, they will naturally think "people played a LOT of X deck my squad would never pla" is indicative of a bad tournament. And they aren't wrong.

@BasicMountain I don't think Ondrej is wrong either. My larger point is I think people are equating "Hoogland said it" with "Wrong and worth QRT-ing for dunks." That's why I said that it feels reminiscent of the old SCG v. Other Circuits nonsense. It's entirely predicated on personal experience
Anyway, just don't take the "chance" to dunk on someone on Twitter. It's not that serious; the Discourse doesn't matter.

Of course, this is shaping up to be GPs vs. SCG Opens Part Two, so this is where I formally say I'm just a dumbass on Twitter who also can remember when a whole pro team stared at Heart of Kiran/Scrapheap Scrounger and registered Implement of Ferocity at a PT.

Like......yeah, I get it. It's Hoogland. I haven't exactly had glowing interactions with the man (what grinder from Chicagoland has?) but he does occasionally make a point about a good number of pros defining tournaments as no-skill bc of lowered exclusivity.

As easy as Hoogland is to dunk on...he isn't exactly WRONG here. Before it was "GPs are harder than SCG Opens" and now it's "Arena events are no-skill".

Idk if Hoogland is the messenger for this argument, but the declaration of some pro circuits as "low-skill" is weird. https://t.co/XbJnNwrmZx

*them* refers to parents or your guardian or whatever. Whoever claimed you.

Like, for better or for worse, excluding adult dependents has a lot to do with how awful it is to change tax policy, and the difficulty of getting your information.

Basically: you should fight being screwed. Please don't piss away parental financial help over 2 grand.

Alternatively, you can sit them down and talk about how much they help with expenses. If they do legit cover half and you can't afford the difference, that fight is NOT worth 2 grand.

Now this is gonna sound VERY callous: if the above is the case, you'll have to take this L.

For college students: I get that you all want a check.

But these are your options: You have a choice. You can file your taxes first, and then you can't be claimed. Or you can file a claim with IRS.

Or you just talk with them about not claiming you.

Generally speaking, filing anyway will trigger an audit that ends up challenging your dependent status. Your parents will likely have to account for the deduction that they don't actually qualify for, and the IRS won't be happy.

If this happened to you, you should file your taxes anyway.
